Rating: 4
Scrumptious! Ive cooked this dish twice and both times it was wonderful. For the roast, I purchase two pork tenderloins (about $14 total) from Costco and tie them together with string to create a 5-lb roast. With my nothing-special, GE, gas oven the roast takes an extra forty minutes to cook. I dont pull the roast out until it is at 150 degrees, and I let it rest a full 25 minutes. Unlike other reviewers, I have used a rack both times Ive cooked this. With burners off, I also deglaze the roast pan with the vermouth and mustard mixture, then transfer the resulting liquids to a sauce pan before beginning the boil- down process. The result is a lovely, tender, fully (but not over) cooked pork roast that is excellent as the main dish for a banquet, and just as good as leftovers the next day or sliced up for sandwiches. Based on the recommendation of a previous reviewer, Ive served the roast with Caramelized-Shallot Mashed Potatoes, and roasted asparagus or wilted spinach. Since nearly every reviewer has warned that it takes longer to cook this roast than the recipe states, keep that in mind when planning your dinner, and choose side dishes that can be completed within the 25 minute rest period. You wont be disappointed.

